{
  "A financial model takes _____ and produces _____.": "",
  "Random data, random results, especially during periods": "",
  "Outputs, inputs regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Assumptions (inputs) and produces projections and decisions (outputs)": "",
  "Only one number, one result, particularly in the context": "",
  "Financial models are structured frameworks that convert assumptions (growth rates, costs, discount rates) into projections (revenue forecasts, valuations, cash flow predictions) to support decision-making.": "",
  "The three essential financial statements in a model are:": "",
  "Income statement, balance sheet, and cash flow statement": "",
  "Only balance sheet and cash flow statement": "",
  "Only income statement": "",
  "Revenue report and expense report only": "",
  "A three-statement model connects the income statement (profitability), balance sheet (financial position), and cash flow statement (cash movements). Changes in one statement flow through to the others.": "",
  "Scenario analysis tests:": "",
  "Only the worst possible outcome within the broader context of analysis analysis": "",
  "Only one variable at a time, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Multiple outcomes such as best case, base case, and worst case with different assumptions": "",
  "Only the most likely outcome when considering all relevant analysis factors": "",
  "Scenario analysis evaluates how model outcomes change under different sets of assumptions, typically testing optimistic, base, and pessimistic cases to understand the range of possible results.": "",
  "Sensitivity analysis differs from scenario analysis because it:": "",
  "Changes nothing under most circumstances involving analysis": "",
  "Only tests the best case without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Changes every variable simultaneously, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Changes ONE variable at a time while holding all others constant to isolate each factor's impact": "",
  "Sensitivity analysis isolates the impact of individual variables by varying one at a time. This helps identify which assumptions have the greatest influence on the model's output.": "",
  "Revenue projection: Year 1 = $100,000 growing at 15% annually. Year 3 revenue is:": "",
  "$132,250": "",
  "$130,000": "",
  "$115,000": "",
  "$145,000": "",
  "Year 3 = $100,000 x (1.15)^2 = $100,000 x 1.3225 = $132,250. Revenue compounds at 15% from Year 1 to Year 3 (two growth periods).": "",
  "If COGS (Cost of Goods Sold) is 40% of revenue, the Year 3 COGS for revenue of $132,250 is:": "",
  "$60,000": "",
  "$48,000": "",
  "$52,900": "",
  "$40,000": "",
  "COGS = $132,250 x 0.40 = $52,900. In financial models, many cost items are projected as a percentage of revenue to maintain consistent relationships.": "",
  "Year 3 gross profit = $132,250 revenue minus $52,900 COGS equals:": "",
  "$79,350": "",
  "$70,000": "",
  "Gross profit = Revenue - COGS = $132,250 - $52,900 = $79,350. This represents a 60% gross margin, which is consistent with the 40% COGS assumption.": "",
  "A DCF (Discounted Cash Flow) model is primarily used to determine:": "",
  "Enterprise value by finding the present value of all future free cash flows": "",
  "Only expenses, based on conventional assumptions about Cash": "",
  "Total revenue without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "The current market price of a stock, based on conventional patterns": "",
  "A DCF model projects future free cash flows and discounts them to present value to estimate the intrinsic value of a business. It is one of the most widely used valuation methods.": "",
