  "Only formats data, based on conventional assumptions about data": "",
  "Automatically calculates outputs across a range of input values for sensitivity analysis": "",
  "Replaces the need for formulas within the broader context of data analysis": "",
  "Only creates charts under most circumstances involving data": "",
  "Excel data tables allow modelers to see how outputs change across a range of inputs (e.g., NPV for discount rates from 5% to 15%) without manually changing each value.": "",
  "Model validation involves:": "",
  "Only verifying that formulas calculate without errors": "",
  "Running the model only once": "",
  "Never checking the model's outputs": "",
  "Comparing model outputs to historical data, industry benchmarks, and logical sense-checks": "",
  "Validation ensures the model is reasonable by cross-checking outputs against historical performance, competitor data, and common-sense benchmarks. A model that projects 50% margins in a 5% margin industry needs investigation.": "",
  "What is a financial model?": "",
  "A regulatory filing required by the SEC": "",
  "A physical replica of a bank building": "",
  "A simple budget spreadsheet with no projections": "",
  "A mathematical representation of a business or investment that uses assumptions to project future financial performance": "",
  "A financial model is a quantitative tool (typically built in a spreadsheet) that translates business assumptions into financial projections, enabling valuation, planning, and decision-making.": "",
  "What is terminal value in a DCF model?": "",
  "The value of all cash flows beyond the explicit forecast period, often 60-80% of total enterprise value": "",
  "Only the last year of the forecast": "",
  "The purchase price of the business": "",
  "The value of the first year's cash flow": "",
  "Terminal value captures the business's value beyond the explicit forecast period (e.g., years 6+ in a 5-year model). It represents the ongoing value of the business and often comprises the majority of total enterprise value.": "",
  "What does GIGO stand for in financial modeling?": "",
  "Garbage In, Garbage Out -- model outputs are only as good as the quality of assumptions": "",
  "General Input, General Output, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Gross Income, Gross Output when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Growth In, Growth Out when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "GIGO reminds modelers that even a perfectly structured model will produce meaningless results if the underlying assumptions are unrealistic. The quality of inputs determines the quality of outputs.": "",
  "What is Monte Carlo simulation?": "",
  "A gambling strategy used in casinos without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "A technique that runs thousands of random scenarios based on probability distributions to produce a range of likely outcomes": "",
  "A method that only tests two scenarios when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "A method that produces exactly one outcome under most circumstances involving Carlo": "",
  "Monte Carlo simulation uses random sampling from probability distributions to run thousands of model iterations, producing a distribution of possible outcomes rather than a single point estimate.": "",
  "What is break-even analysis in a financial model?": "",
  "The point where stock price matches book value": "",
  "The point where the company achieves maximum profit": "",
  "The combination of price, volume, and costs where total revenue equals total costs (zero profit)": "",
  "The amount of debt a company can take on": "",
  "Break-even analysis identifies the sales volume (or revenue level) at which a business covers all its costs -- both fixed and variable -- with zero profit or loss. It is a critical viability threshold.": "",
  "What are the key assumptions that should be documented in any financial model?": "",
  "Only the final valuation number, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Only the company name and date within the broader context of assumptions analysis": "",
  "Only revenue projections according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Growth rates, margins, discount rate, tax rate, capital expenditures, and working capital needs": "",
  "Documenting all key assumptions allows stakeholders to evaluate reasonableness, update inputs when conditions change, and audit the model. Undocumented assumptions create opaque models that cannot be challenged or improved.": "",
  "What does 'color coding' mean in financial modeling best practices?": "",
  "Using color to indicate profitable vs. unprofitable scenarios": "",
  "Using different colors to distinguish inputs (blue), formulas (black), and links to other sheets (green)": "",
  "Highlighting cells that contain errors in red": "",
  "Making the model visually attractive for presentations": "",
  "Standard modeling practice uses blue for hard-coded inputs, black for calculated formulas, and green for links to other sheets. This convention helps users quickly identify which cells contain assumptions they can change.": "",
  "What is the perpetuity growth method for calculating terminal value?": "",
  "TV = Revenue x Growth Rate, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "TV = Total Assets - Total Liabilities when considering all relevant cash factors": "",
  "TV = FCF x (1 + g) / (r - g), where FCF is the final year's free cash flow, g is the perpetual growth rate, and r is the discount rate": "",
  "TV = Last Year's Revenue x P/E Ratio, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "The perpetuity growth method assumes free cash flows grow at a constant rate forever beyond the forecast period. The formula TV = FCF x (1+g)/(r-g) capitalizes the growing cash stream into a single terminal value.": "",
  "What is the output of a Monte Carlo simulation?": "",
  "A probability distribution showing the likelihood of various outcomes": "",
  "A perfect prediction of the future": "",
  "Only the average result": "",
  "A single definitive answer": "",
  "Monte Carlo produces a distribution of outcomes, allowing statements like 'there is a 90% probability that NPV exceeds zero' or 'the expected valuation range is $50M to $80M with 80% confidence.'": "",
  "What concepts does financial modeling integrate?": "",
  "TVM, NPV, IRR, break-even analysis, growth projections, and scenario analysis -- the culmination of financial math skills": "",
