  "Only spreadsheet formatting according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Only technology skills, which is consistent with how financial mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "Financial modeling is the practical application of all financial math concepts. It brings together TVM, NPV, IRR, break-even, projections, and scenario analysis into a unified framework for real-world decision-making.": "",
  "A DCF model projects Year 5 free cash flow of $1 million. Using the perpetuity growth method with g = 3% and r = 10%, the terminal value is approximately:": "",
  "$14.7 million": "",
  "$20 million": "",
  "$30 million": "",
  "$10 million": "",
  "TV = FCF x (1+g)/(r-g) = $1M x 1.03 / (0.10 - 0.03) = $1.03M / 0.07 = $14.71M. This captures the value of all cash flows growing at 3% perpetually beyond Year 5.": "",
  "A startup projects Year 1 revenue of $100,000 growing 15% annually. By Year 5, projected revenue will be approximately:": "",
  "$250,000": "",
  "$160,000": "",
  "$175,000": "",
  "$200,000": "",
  "Year 5 = $100,000 x (1.15)^4 = $100,000 x 1.7490 = $174,901, approximately $175,000. Note: from Year 1 to Year 5 is 4 compounding periods.": "",
  "A business has fixed costs of $60,000 per year, a selling price of $25 per unit, and variable costs of $10 per unit. How many units must it sell to break even?": "",
  "6,000 units": "",
  "10,000 units": "",
  "2,400 units": "",
  "4,000 units": "",
  "Break-even units = Fixed Costs / (Price - Variable Cost) = $60,000 / ($25 - $10) = $60,000 / $15 = 4,000 units. At 4,000 units, total revenue ($100,000) equals total costs ($60,000 fixed + $40,000 variable).": "",
  "A financial model shows base case NPV = $500,000, best case NPV = $1,200,000, and worst case NPV = -$200,000. What does this scenario analysis reveal?": "",
  "Only the base case matters": "",
  "The average NPV of $500,000 is the only relevant figure": "",
  "The project is positive in the base and best cases but has downside risk -- the worst case suggests possible value destruction": "",
  "The project should be rejected because the worst case is negative": "",
  "The scenario analysis shows the project is likely profitable (positive in base and best cases) but carries risk in adverse conditions. Management must assess the probability of each scenario and whether the potential $200,000 loss is acceptable.": "",
  "A sensitivity analysis varies the discount rate from 8% to 14% for a project. NPV falls from $120,000 at 8% to $5,000 at 14%. This tells the analyst:": "",
  "The project should be accepted at any rate according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Only the 8% rate should be used regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "The project's viability is highly sensitive to the discount rate, and a small increase could make it marginal": "",
  "The discount rate does not matter, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A 6-percentage-point increase in the discount rate reduces NPV from $120,000 to just $5,000 -- a 96% decline. The project is highly rate-sensitive, meaning the analyst must have strong confidence in the discount rate for the investment to be worthwhile.": "",
  "A Monte Carlo simulation of a real estate investment runs 10,000 iterations. The results show a 75% probability that IRR exceeds 12% and a 10% probability that IRR falls below 5%. An investor with a 10% hurdle rate should:": "",
  "Consider accepting since there is a strong probability (75%) of exceeding the hurdle rate, while understanding the 10% downside risk": "",
  "Ignore the simulation and rely on a single-point estimate": "",
  "Reject the project because there is some chance of underperformance": "",
  "Accept only if the probability reaches 100%": "",
  "Monte Carlo provides probabilistic insights rather than a single answer. A 75% chance of exceeding the hurdle rate is favorable, but the investor should understand and accept the 10% chance of a return below 5%.": "",
  "In a three-statement model, when net income on the income statement increases, how does this affect the other statements?": "",
  "The balance sheet decreases while cash flow increases": "",
  "The other statements remain unchanged": "",
  "Higher net income flows to retained earnings on the balance sheet and increases cash from operations on the cash flow statement": "",
  "Only the cash flow statement is affected": "",
  "The three statements are interconnected: net income from the income statement adds to retained earnings (equity) on the balance sheet and serves as the starting point for the cash flow statement, demonstrating how changes cascade through the model.": "",
